(42, 23, 36, 40, 27, 34, 34, 'offering him vinegar', 'Mocking and Offering Vinegar', 'Both passages emphasize the act of offering vinegar to Jesus during his crucifixion. Luke highlights the soldiers mocking him while providing vinegar, while Matthew notes the vinegar was mingled with gall, indicating a shared moment of derision.', 'parallel', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 23, 36, 41, 15, 36, 36, 'offering him vinegar', 'Mocking and Offering Vinegar', 'Both passages emphasize the act of offering vinegar to Jesus during his crucifixion. The soldiers mock him while providing vinegar, highlighting the scorn he faced. This connection illustrates a shared moment of derision in the narrative.', 'parallel', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 23, 36, 41, 15, 19, 20, 'mocked him', 'Mocking of Jesus', 'Both passages emphasize the mocking of Jesus by soldiers. In Luke, they offer him vinegar, while in Mark, they physically abuse and mock him before leading him to crucifixion.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 23, 36, 42, 23, 11, 11, 'mocked him', 'Mocking of Jesus', 'Both passages emphasize the mocking of Jesus by those in authority. In Luke 23:11, Herod and his men mock him, while in Luke 23:36, the soldiers also mock him, highlighting a theme of ridicule during his trial.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 23, 36, 43, 19, 28, 30, 'offering him vinegar', 'Mocking and Thirst of Jesus', 'Both passages emphasize the mocking of Jesus and his thirst during the crucifixion. The soldiers'' offering of vinegar in Luke connects directly to Jesus'' declaration of thirst in John, highlighting the fulfillment of scripture.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 23, 38, 40, 27, 37, 37, 'THIS IS THE KING OF THE JEWS', 'Accusation of Jesus'' Kingship', 'Both passages emphasize the declaration of Jesus as ''THE KING OF THE JEWS.'' This connection highlights the significance of this title in the context of his crucifixion.', 'parallel', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 23, 38, 41, 15, 26, 26, 'THE KING OF THE JEWS', 'Superscription of Accusation', 'Both passages emphasize the inscription identifying Jesus as ''THE KING OF THE JEWS.'' This connection highlights the consistency in the portrayal of Jesus'' title during his crucifixion.', 'parallel', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 23, 38, 43, 19, 19, 22, 'THIS IS THE KING OF THE JEWS', 'Title of the Superscription', 'Both passages emphasize the inscription placed above Jesus during the crucifixion, identifying him as ''THE KING OF THE JEWS.'' This connection highlights the consistency in the way Jesus'' identity is presented across the Gospels.', 'parallel', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 23, 38, 41, 15, 32, 32, 'THIS IS THE KING OF THE JEWS', 'Connection of Kingship in Crucifixion', 'Both passages emphasize the title ''King'' in relation to Jesus. In Luke, the inscription declares him ''THE KING OF THE JEWS,'' while Mark references him as ''Christ the King of Israel.'' This connection highlights the mockery and challenge to his kingship during the crucifixion.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 23, 38, 42, 23, 3, 3, 'KING OF THE JEWS', 'Connection of Kingship in Luke', 'Both passages emphasize the title ''King of the Jews.'' In Luke 23:3, Pilate directly questions Jesus about this kingship, while Luke 23:38 presents the formal declaration of this title at the crucifixion.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 23, 38, 40, 27, 11, 11, 'KING OF THE JEWS', 'Jesus as King of the Jews', 'Both passages emphasize Jesus'' identity as the King of the Jews. In Luke, the superscription explicitly states this title, while in Matthew, the governor directly questions Jesus about it.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 23, 38, 43, 19, 3, 3, 'THIS IS THE KING OF THE JEWS', 'Recognition of Jesus'' Kingship', 'Both passages emphasize the title ''King of the Jews'' in relation to Jesus. The mockery in John 19:3 complements the declaration in Luke 23:38, highlighting the perception of Jesus'' kingship during his crucifixion.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(42, 23, 39, 40, 27, 44, 44, NULL, 'Mockery of Jesus on the Cross', 'Both passages emphasize the mocking of Jesus by those crucified alongside him. The SOURCE verse highlights one malefactor''s challenge to Jesus'' identity, while the TARGET passage notes that both thieves engaged in this derision.', 'parallel', 0.37, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
